[4] Pakistan - Balochistan: 10 new cases
Date: 13 Dec 2012
Source: The International News [edited]
http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-13-19455-10-new-polio-cases-reported-in-Balochistan


10 new polio cases reported in Balochistan
------------------------------------------
The exertions of the Balochistan government to save the children from the crippling polio disease have turned abortive as at least 10 new cases of the crippling virus, like that of a 2 year old [male], have been reported in the province in the last few weeks.

Of them 9 cases have been reported from the districts of Kila Abdullah Khan and one from Pishin, officials of the World Health Organization (WHO) confided while talking to The News on Wednesday [12 Dec 2012]. Apart from these, 4 cases of wild polio virus of type 1 had been reported in the province this year [2012]. Official sources confided that on Wednesday last [?5 Dec 2012], the last day of the 1st of 3 special anti-polio campaigns, 7530 families refused to administer the anti-polio drops to their children in Quetta, Kila Abdullah and Pishin districts. Of them, 2794 families refused at Quetta, 2788 refusal cases reported at Pishin, while 1948 families refused in Kila Abdullah.

It is worth mentioning here that the infectious disease has been eliminated in developed nations but persists in parts of Nigeria, Afghanistan, and Pakistan.

Pakistan reported 56 cases of the crippling virus in 2012 that had been reduced from 199 in 2011, while Afghanistan has reported 38. Most of the Afghan and Pakistani cases have occurred along their porous border.

In its report, the Independent Monitoring Board (IMB) of global polio eradication initiative, has recommended the International Health Regulations Expert Review Committee to issue urgently a standing recommendation by May 2013 that will introduce pre-travel vaccination or vaccination checks in Afghanistan, Nigeria and Pakistan until national transmission is stopped. "No country should allow a citizen from any endemic polio state to cross their border without a valid vaccination certificate," the IMB recommendations added.

Soon after the IMB report, a high-level meeting was held with the chief minister of Balochistan, Nawab Muhammad Aslam Raisani, in the chair last week. It decided to launch 3 special polio campaigns in the polio-affected areas. It has been [learned] that the ways and means were discussed to eradicate the polio completely from the province. The chief minister expressed his dismay over the presence of the increased number of polio cases in the province. He, on the occasion, said the government would mobilise all its available resources and manpower to achieve the target of "Polio-free Balochistan".

The chief minister said though effective steps are being taken for eradication of the crippling disease in the province, there is still much room to do a lot to achieve complete success in this regard.

On the occasion, the chief secretary expressed the resolve to eradicate the disease from the province saying that the major reason behind the new outbreak is the administrative issue, which needs to be resolved. He directed that it must be ensured to administer the anti-polio drops to every kid in the affected districts.

[byline: Muhammad Ejaz Khan]

