[The above series of reports highlights the challenges to a final interruption of poliovirus (both wild and vaccine derived) transmission/circulation in the 3 remaining polio endemic countries in the world -- Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Nigeria. In both Afghanistan and Pakistan unacceptable violence has been directed at polio vaccination teams, resulting in the deaths of 8 polio campaign workers over the past few weeks. The room for international outcry and action is there. It is totally incomprehensible to this moderator how these violent acts can be directed at humanitarian workers whose sole "infraction" is trying to eradicate a disease responsible for death and disability of predominantly children in these countries.

If one looks at the global polio update as of 12 Dec 2012 from the Polio Eradication Initiative (in section [5] above] one sees that at present the only countries where there are documented wild poliovirus (WPV) cases are the 3 remaining polio endemic countries -- Afghanistan, Pakistan and Nigeria. But, there continue to be paralytic polio cases associated with infection from circulating vaccine derived polioviruses (cVDPV) this year (2012) in Kenya, Somalia, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Yemen, Chad and the 3 remaining polio endemic countries -- Afghanistan, Pakistan and Nigeria. As mentioned in previous polio posts, both WPV and cVDPV circulation occur in areas where there are suboptimal polio vaccination coverages. The challenges have been to sustain high levels of polio vaccination coverage after WPV transmission has been interrupted in an area and the population no longer sees an urgency in vaccinating their children as the disease appears no longer to be a threat.

The obvious concerns here are that while presently the only countries with documented WPV transmission are the 3 remaining polio endemic countries, the danger of reintroduction of WPV to other countries whose vaccination coverages have declined is ever present (and has occurred through the years -- recurrent cases in other African countries, Indonesia, China to name a few of the instances in the not too distant past).

For maps of countries where there have been confirmed cases due to WPV infections in 2011 and 2012, see http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Poliocasesworldwide.aspx.
For a map of countries where there have been confirmed cases due to cVDPV infections
during the preceding 6 months, and tables showing the number of cases of cVDPV by year, country and cVDPV type since 2000, see: http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Circulatingvaccinederivedpoliovirus.aspx. - Mod.MPP]
